comments.body:
One Optimization we can have here is to lock only when we need to populate firsBatchTimestamp, for example:
in LogSegment.scala , we can add:
def isFirstBatchTimestampLoaded : Boolean = {
    rollingBasedTimestamp match {
      case Some(t) => true
      case _ => false
    }
  }

In log.scala, we can have:

@threadsafe
  private[log] def getFirstBatchTimestampForSegments2(segments: Iterable[LogSegment]): Iterable[Long] = {

    val needLoadTimestampSegments = segments.filter {
      segment =>
        !segment.isFirstBatchTimestampLoaded
    }

    if (needLoadTimestampSegments.nonEmpty) {
      lock synchronized {
        needLoadTimestampSegments.foreach {
          segment =>
            segment.loadFirstBatchTimestamp()
        }
      }
    }

    segments.map {
      segment =>
        segment.getFirstBatchTimestampWithoutLoading()
    }
  }

This optimization will reduce lock contention on the log.  However, each time we call log.logSegments,  we are acquiring the locks.  log.logSegments has been called multiple times (e.g, cleanableOffsets, LogToClean, etc.) during the log compaction . 

The choice here is :  reduced potential lock contention versus simplified code.

